<p><a name="fall_2013_bannister_wins_best_presentation_award"></a><b>Bannister Wins Best Presentation Award</b></p>
<div class="img_caption_left"><img alt="photo: Michael Bannister" height="90" src="../../../bin/img/photos/noteworthy/MichaelBannister-noteworthy.jpg"/>
<p><b> Michael <br/> Bannister</b></p>
</div>
<p>
<b>Michael Bannister</b>, a computer science Ph.D. candidate associated with the Center for Algorithms and Theory of Computing, has won the best presentation award at the 
<a href="http://gd2013.labri.fr/">21st International Symposium on Graph Drawing</a>, 
held Sept. 23-25 in Bordeaux, France. The award, which was offered for the first time, was determined by the votes of conference participants.
</p>
<p>
The presentation for which Bannister won the award, &#8220;Superpatterns and Universal Point Sets,&#8221; concerned his research with fellow graduate students 
<b>Zhanpeng Cheng</b> and <b>Will Devanny</b>, as well as Professor <b>David Eppstein</b>, about new connections between information visualization and the mathematics of permutation patterns.
</p>
<p>&#160;</p>
<!-- -->
<!-- -->
<!-- -->
<!-- -->
